        <div type="edition" xml:lang="fre">
         <p>
            <seg xml:lang="fre">Vers midi nous passames près d’un grand endroit situé en Bulgarie, sur l’eminence du rivage, qui est habité par des Bugariens et Turcs. On y decouvre au dessus une vieille eglise grequé, qui tombe en ruine et deux Mosquées à minarets. Au milieu il y a une palanque à la Turque ceinte de hautes palisades, à peu près comme étoit celle de Raizena l’an 1737, de là elle porte le nom de Lan-palanka.</seg>
          </p>
        </div>
        <div type="commentary" subtype="general">
         <ab> The text is written between <date type="initial">None</date> and <date type="final">None</date>.
           The name of the monument is <name type="source">Lan Palanka</name> or <name type="contemporary">Lom</name>. According to the text, it is It is located <location>
            <geo>43.8317; 23.23793</geo> <geo>https://www.geonames.org/729581/lom.html</geo>
         </location>.Now it is located here: <location type="original"><geo>None;None</geo> <geo>None</geo></location>, in <name type="current" xml:lang="None">None</name>.
         The internal date in the document is <date>30.06.1740</date>.
        We have evidence that the object was obseved in <location type="subsequent1"><geo>43.822942 ; 23.236013</geo> </location>.
        The object has been seen in <location type="subsequent2"><geo>43.83200; 23.236789</geo> </location>  </ab>
        </div>
         <div type="commentary" subtype="additional">
            <p>
              <seg>Captain Schad describes Lom in the Ottoman period, explicitly mentioning that the settlement was a type of palanca. In today's. Lom are also the ruins of the ancient fortress of Almus.  The church mentioned by Shad probably refers to the church of St. Nicholas the Old (Borun Church), a medieval church destroyed during the Ottoman period and rebuilt in 1818. </seg>
            </p>
